<blockquote>
<p>But if the reader has to ask clarifying questions about what's actually written on the page, that's the author's fault.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I am going to disagree with this a bit. Sometimes some readers just aren't going to get it, and you risk over explaining to the majority if you try to explain everything to everybody.</p>
<p>For example, I have gone over <a href="/scp-2323">SCP-2323</a>'s comments multiple times and I still don't see how I can address some of the questions there, which seem to be caused by a couple of readers not understanding what memes are really supposed to be or not understanding that the Foundation primarily contains things that are anomalous. I can't actually explain memetics or the Foundation in the article as these topics are well outside the scope of an SCP article. The article itself is highly successful and it would probably be stupid to try to &quot;fix&quot; it when it clearly ain't broke anyway.</p>
<p>Sometimes people are going to ask clarifying questions that aren't the author's fault because they missed something when they read it, because they aren't familiar with something that is key but outside the scope of the article, or because they simply failed to make a connection.</p>

							</div>

								
